Clothing is an expression of ourselves; a visual shorthand for who we are & what we like. Our desire for that isn't going anywhere, nor does it have to, but the planet is dying & garment workers are suffering. We have to be realistic, responsible and learn to say no to ourselves

Borrow clothes from your friends ! Instead of buying it, hire something really nice for events like weddings ! Spend time trying out different outfit pairings rather than falling back on the familiar which will get boring fast and stop feeling as fresh when you're going out !

This can be problematic for some people, but where it isn't, take note of your measurements. Most online stores will cite the measurements for their sizing and where sizes vary wildly between brands, this can save you on ordering several sizes and the cumbersome returns process

Store clothes as best you can. Hang & fold them, air dry rather than tumble dry wherever able, don't leave stains to set, pay attention to label instructions, cold wash if possible, separate whites from colours. Don't treat anything as disposable if you want it to last

Textile recycling points can be a better choice than charity shops, particularly if you're giving away some knackered or stained old fit that a volunteer is going to then have to dispose of somewhere anyway. It's a bit more effort but if you can do it, then you really should be

Be pragmatic in buying habits, for instance in winter it is likely you will wear a coat over your outfit so make that your investment or statement piece. Find a silhouette you like on yourself & guide choices around that - you're more likely to get bored of a print than a cut
Always use protector on leather and suede even if they are brand new. Buy at-home waterproofer for your jackets and outdoor clothes

Certain textiles are written off once damaged but there's always a way - for torn polyester, PVC or waterproof clothes, you can buy repair patches which you iron or glue on. A bottle of hot water can do the job if you have no iron. They're cheap & come in any colour you need
Some dry cleaners and fabric shops will offer a repair service which is often low cost and great if you are unable to carry out repairs yourself

If you can, learn to sew ! Learn to knit ! Learn to crochet ! These are useful skills to have anyway, and once you can do this, not only can you repair clothes, you can alter or make them - change buttons, adjust sizing, repair a broken zip or elastic, make a scarf, etc

Do not be afraid to dye your clothes ! You'll need dye that is compatible with whatever textile you're looking to dye, but it can bring a colour back to its original vibrance, or change it entirely. It can also conceal marks that even stain remover cannot get rid of

Buy a handheld steamer - they're cheap, better for your clothes than an iron, faster to use, and allow you to clean things like coats or shoes which can require specialist laundering. Hot steam is also antibacterial, refreshes your clothes, and smoothes out awkward creases‚ú®

Look for clothing in materials like linen, satin and cotton. These materials are not expensive by default, they're better for the environment and for you, they hold their shape and colour for longer, and are far less likely to shrink in the wash

Fabric depillers are really good for when you find something secondhand that with a bit of care, could be looking next to new e.g. if the elbows or cuffs look a bit fuzzy. Pilling is a result of friction so getting rid of it can bring your clothes back to the 'unworn' look

Get a fabric depiller. Fabric pilling is that rough, bobbled texture and it can happen to all textiles, not just cheap clothes, and particularly to wool. A depiller removes that and makes your clothes look new and fresh again. If you're brave, you can also use a razor

7. Industrial peat extraction sites are especially at risk as the albedo effect will increase the temperature within the peat and further lower the water level leading to enhanced CO2 emissions and loss of peat (and carbon) through wind erosion. https://t.co/rdllg01wrk
